2.1.3.1 Penalty method
The penalty method was one of the ﬁrst to be used. It utilizes the non exactitude of the numerical resolution of the system to approximate, also, the contact conditions. The conditions of contact are thus not strictly respected and the interpenetration and reversible tangential slip are permitted. Hence, the penalty method is not consistent. In fact this method implies that the contact surface does not restrict penetration and reversible slip but resists them: the deeper the penetration the higher the resisting reaction. The physical interpretation of this method is to represent the master surface as a serie of springs with zero initial length and a rigidity equal to the penalization parameter n. It has the advantage of being very simple for implementation what makes it, till today, one of the most widespread methods.

